e and Staffordshire). With the exception of Alston in Cumbria, which is formed with the Old Norse personal name <i>Halfdan</i>, these placenames all consist of an Old English personal name + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, for example <i>Ælfsige</i> in the case of Alstone in Gloucestershire."],"variants":[{"name":"Aston","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Ad(e)stan</i>, which is usually from Old English <i>Æthelstān</i> (see   Alston  ). It may also be from the much rarer Old English name <i>Ēadstān</i>.","habitational name from any of several places in England called Aston. Most were named with Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. In a few cases the first element is <i>æsc</i> ‘ash tree’."]},{"name":"Allston","meanings":["English: variant of   Alston  ."]},{"name":"Hailstone","meanings":["habitational name from Hailstone Hill in Wiltshire or Hailstone Farm in Gloucestershire, the former of which may be derived from Old English <i>hālig-stān</i> ‘holy stone’ or <i>hagolstān</i> ‘hailstone’ (Middle English <i>hawelston</i>, <i>hailston</i>).","from <i>Ailstan</i>, a variant of the Old English personal name <i>Æthelstān</i> (‘noble’ + ‘stone’), with prosthetic initial <i>H-</i>. The first element of the Old English name developed from <i>Æthel-</i> to <i>Ægel-</i> and then to <i>Ail-</i>; it was often further shortened to <i>Al-</i> (see   Alston  ).","English:"]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Alston was born in 1401, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1401–":"1401–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1401–Male":"1401–Surnud","1401":"1401","Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1401–":"1401–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1401–Male":"14